0:14:25.173,000 --> 0:14:31,000
(Applause)

297
0:14:33,000 --> 0:14:35,000
But actually, I believe there are really two Microsofts.

298
0:14:35.726,000 --> 0:14:38,000
There's the old one, responsible for Windows and Office.

299
0:14:38.829,000 --> 0:14:42,000
They're dying to throw the whole thing out and start fresh, but they can't.

300
0:14:42.867,000 --> 0:14:45,000
They're locked in, because so many add-ons and other company stuff

301
0:14:46.591,000 --> 0:14:48,000
locks into the old 1982 chassis.

302
0:14:49.236,000 --> 0:14:5,000
But there's also a new Microsoft,

303
0:14:50.85,000 --> 0:14:53,000
that's really doing good, simple interface designs.

304
0:14:54.365,000 --> 0:14:55,000
I liked the Media Center PC.

305
0:14:55.945,000 --> 0:14:56,000
I liked the Microsoft SPOT Watch.

306
0:14:57.725,000 --> 0:14:59,000
The Wireless Watch flopped miserably in the market,

307
0:15:00.702,000 --> 0:15:03,000
but it wasn't because it wasn't simply and beautifully designed.

308
0:15:03.774,000 --> 0:15:04,000
But let's put it this way:

309
0:15:05.044,000 --> 0:15:07,000
would you pay $10 a month to have a watch

310
0:15:07.559,000 --> 0:15:1,000
that has to be recharged every night like your cell phone,

311
0:15:10.841,000 --> 0:15:12,000
and stops working when you leave your area code?

312
0:15:13.404,000 --> 0:15:15,000
(Laughter)

313
0:15:16.026,000 --> 0:15:18,000
So, the signs might indicate

314
0:15:18.551,000 --> 0:15:2,000
that the complexity crunch is only going to get worse.

315
0:15:21.412,000 --> 0:15:22,000
So is there any hope?

316
0:15:23.089,000 --> 0:15:25,000
The screens are getting smaller, people are illuminating,

317
0:15:25.812,000 --> 0:15:26,000
putting manuals in the boxes,

318
0:15:27.233,000 --> 0:15:29,000
things are coming out at a faster pace.

319
0:15:3,000 --> 0:15:33,000
It's funny -- when Steve Jobs came back to Apple in 1997,

320
0:15:33.417,000 --> 0:15:35,000
after 12 years away, it was the MacWorld Expo --

321
0:15:36.266,000 --> 0:15:39,000
he came to the stage in that black turtleneck and jeans,

322
0:15:39.432,000 --> 0:15:4,000
and he sort of did this.

323
0:15:40.608,000 --> 0:15:42,000
The crowd went wild, but I had just seen --

324
0:15:43,000 --> 0:15:44,000
I'm like, where have I seen this before?

325
0:15:44.95,000 --> 0:15:45,000
I had just seen the movie "Evita" --

326
0:15:46.783,000 --> 0:15:49,000
(Laughter)

327
0:15:49.892,000 --> 0:15:5,000
with Madonna,

328
0:15:51.074,000 --> 0:15:52,000
and I'm like, you know what?

329
0:15:52.846,000 --> 0:15:55,000
I've got to do one about Steve Jobs.

330
0:15:55.967,000 --> 0:15:56,000
(Music)

331
0:15:56.999,000 --> 0:15:59,000
It won't be easy. You'll think I'm strange.

332
0:16:00.039,000 --> 0:16:01,000
(Laughter)

333
0:16:01.207,000 --> 0:16:03,000
When I try to explain why I'm back,

334
0:16:03.54,000 --> 0:16:06,000
after telling the press Apple's future is black.

335
0:16:06.655,000 --> 0:16:08,000
You won't believe me.

336
0:16:09.274,000 --> 0:16:13,000
All that you see is a kid in his teens who started out in a garage

337
0:16:14,000 --> 0:16:16,000
with only a buddy named Woz.

338
0:16:17,000 --> 0:16:18,000
(Laughter)

339
0:16:18.576,000 --> 0:16:19,000
You try rhyming with garage!

340
0:16:20.333,000 --> 0:16:22,000
(Laughter)

341
0:16:22.799,000 --> 0:16:24,000
Don't cry for me, Cupertino.

342
0:16:25.698,000 --> 0:16:26,000
(Laughter)

343
0:16:27.044,000 --> 0:16:29,000
The truth is, I never left you.

344
0:16:3,000 --> 0:16:33,000
I know the ropes now, know what the tricks are.

345
0:16:33.559,000 --> 0:16:36,000
I made a fortune over at Pixar.

346
0:16:37,000 --> 0:16:38,000
(Laughter)

347
0:16:38.063,000 --> 0:16:4,000
Don't cry for me, Cupertino.

348
0:16:41.182,000 --> 0:16:44,000
I've still got the drive and vision.

349
0:16:44.519,000 --> 0:16:47,000
I still wear sandals in any weather.

350
0:16:47.995,000 --> 0:16:48,000
It's just that these days,

351
0:16:5,000 --> 0:16:51,000
they're Gucci leather.

352
0:16:52,000 --> 0:16:53,000
(Laughter)

353
0:16:54,000 --> 0:17:,000
(Applause)

354
0:17:01.258,000 --> 0:17:02,000
Thank you.

355
0:17:02.815,000 --> 0:17:06,000
So Steve Jobs had always believed in simplicity and elegance and beauty.

356
0:17:07.547,000 --> 0:17:08,000
And the truth is,

357
0:17:09.468,000 --> 0:17:11,000
for years I was a little depressed,

358
0:17:11.62,000 --> 0:17:13,000
because Americans obviously did not value it,

359
0:17:13.917,000 --> 0:17:15,000
because the Mac had three percent market share,

360
0:17:16.218,000 --> 0:17:17,000
Windows had 95 percent market share --

361
0:17:18.099,000 --> 0:17:2,000
people did not think it was worth putting a price on it.

362
0:17:21,000 --> 0:17:22,000
So I was a little depressed.

363
0:17:22.815,000 --> 0:17:23,000
And then I heard Al Gore's talk,

364
0:17:24.396,000 --> 0:17:26,000
and I realized I didn't know the meaning of depressed.

365
0:17:26.959,000 --> 0:17:27,000
(Laughter)

366
0:17:28,000 --> 0:17:29,000
But it turns out I was wrong, right?

367
0:17:29.761,000 --> 0:17:3,000
Because the iPod came out,

368
0:17:31.518,000 --> 0:17:33,000
and it violated every bit of common wisdom.

369
0:17:34.16,000 --> 0:17:36,000
Other products cost less; other products had more features,

370
0:17:37.16,000 --> 0:17:39,000
they had voice recorders and FM transmitters.

371
0:17:39.921,000 --> 0:17:42,000
The other products were backed by Microsoft, with an open standard,

372
0:17:43.167,000 --> 0:17:44,000
not Apple's propriety standard.

373
0:17:44.905,000 --> 0:17:46,000
But the iPod won -- this is the one they wanted.

374
0:17:47.501,000 --> 0:17:49,000
The lesson was: simplicity sells.

375
0:17:49.788,000 --> 0:17:51,000
And there are signs that the industry is getting the message.

376
0:17:52.686,000 --> 0:17:55,000
This is a little company that's done very well with simplicity and elegance.

377
0:17:56.301,000 --> 0:17:57,000
The Sonos thing -- it's catching on.

378
0:17:58.064,000 --> 0:17:59,000
I've got just a couple examples.

379
0:17:59.786,000 --> 0:18:02,000
Physically, a really cool, elegant thinking coming along lately.

380
0:18:03.486,000 --> 0:18:04,000
When you have a digital camera,

381
0:18:05.463,000 --> 0:18:08,000
how do you get the pictures back to your computer?

382
0:18:08.73,000 --> 0:18:1,000
Well, you either haul around a USB cable,

383
0:18:11.096,000 --> 0:18:13,000
or you buy a card reader and haul that around.

384
0:18:13.276,000 --> 0:18:14,000
Either one, you're going to lose.

385
0:18:14.887,000 --> 0:18:16,000
What I do is, I take out the memory card,

386
0:18:17.37,000 --> 0:18:22,000
and I fold it in half, revealing USB contacts.

387
0:18:22.739,000 --> 0:18:24,000
I just stick it in the computer, offload the pictures,

388
0:18:25.421,000 --> 0:18:26,000
put it right back in the camera.

389
0:18:26.984,000 --> 0:18:27,000
I never have to lose anything.

390
0:18:28.808,000 --> 0:18:29,000
Here's another example.

391
0:18:30.369,000 --> 0:18:33,000
Chris, you're the source of all power. Will you be my power plug?

392
0:18:33.463,000 --> 0:18:35,000
Chris Anderson: Oh yeah. DP: Hold that and don't let go.

393
0:18:36.227,000 --> 0:18:38,000
You might've seen this, this is Apple's new laptop.

394
0:18:38.672,000 --> 0:18:4,000
This the power cord. It hooks on like this.

395
0:18:40.72,000 --> 0:18:43,000
And I'm sure every one of you has done this at some point in your lives,

396
0:18:44.141,000 --> 0:18:45,000
or one of your children.

397
0:18:45.34,000 --> 0:18:47,000
You walk along -- and I'm about to pull this onto the floor.

398
0:18:48.189,000 --> 0:18:49,000
I don't care. It's a loaner.

399
0:18:49.549,000 --> 0:18:5,000
Here we go. Whoa!

400
0:18:50.756,000 --> 0:18:53,000
It's magnetic -- it doesn't pull the laptop onto the floor.

401
0:18:53.849,000 --> 0:18:57,000
(Applause)

402
0:18:58,000 --> 0:18:59,000
In my very last example --

403
0:18:59.993,000 --> 0:19:02,000
I do a lot of my work using speech recognition software.

404
0:19:03.993,000 --> 0:19:05,000
And I'll just -- you have to be kind of quiet

405
0:19:06.247,000 --> 0:19:07,000
because the software is nervous.

406
0:19:08.524,000 --> 0:19:1,000
Speech recognition software is really great

407
0:19:10.628,000 --> 0:19:12,000
for doing emails very quickly; period.

408
0:19:13.182,000 --> 0:19:15,000
Like, I get hundreds of them a day; period.

409
0:19:15.845,000 --> 0:19:18,000
And it's not just what I dictate that it writes down; period.

410
0:19:19.16,000 --> 0:19:22,000
I also use this feature called voice macros; period.

411
0:19:23.92,000 --> 0:19:24,000
Correct "dissuade."

412
0:19:28.999,000 --> 0:19:29,000
Not "just."

413
0:19:32.248,000 --> 0:19:33,000
Ok, this is not an ideal situation,

414
0:19:33.954,000 --> 0:19:35,000
because it's getting the echo from the hall and stuff.

415
0:19:36.517,000 --> 0:19:4,000
The point is, I can respond to people very quickly by saying a short word,

416
0:19:40.777,000 --> 0:19:42,000
and having it write out a much longer thing.

417
0:19:42.873,000 --> 0:19:44,000
So if somebody sends me a fan letter, I'll say,

418
0:19:45.263,000 --> 0:19:46,000
"Thanks for that."

419
0:19:46.444,000 --> 0:19:48,000
[Thank you so much for taking the time to write ...]

420
0:19:48.975,000 --> 0:19:49,000
(Laughter)

421
0:19:5,000 --> 0:19:52,000
(Applause)

422
0:19:53,000 --> 0:19:57,000
And conversely, if somebody sends me hate mail --

423
0:19:57.462,000 --> 0:19:59,000
which happens daily --

424
0:19:59.788,000 --> 0:20:01,000
I say, "Piss off."

425
0:20:04.508,000 --> 0:20:05,000
(Laughter)

426
0:20:05.849,000 --> 0:20:07,000
[I admire your frankness ...]

427
0:20:08.345,000 --> 0:20:09,000
(Laughter)

428
0:20:1,000 --> 0:20:15,000
(Applause)

429
0:20:15.377,000 --> 0:20:17,000
So that's my dirty little secret. Don't tell anyone.

430
0:20:18,000 --> 0:20:19,000
(Laughter)

431
0:20:19.139,000 --> 0:20:21,000
So the point is -- this is a really interesting story.

432
0:20:22,000 --> 0:20:23,000
This is version eight of this software,

433
0:20:23.902,000 --> 0:20:25,000
and do you know what they put in version eight?

434
0:20:26.124,000 --> 0:20:29,000
No new features. It's never happened before in software!

435
0:20:29.21,000 --> 0:20:3,000
The company put no new features.

436
0:20:30.965,000 --> 0:20:33,000
They just said, "We'll make this software work right." Right?

437
0:20:34.604,000 --> 0:20:37,000
Because for years, people had bought this software, tried it out --

438
0:20:37.844,000 --> 0:20:38,000
95 percent accuracy was all they got,

439
0:20:39.669,000 --> 0:20:4,000
which means one in 20 words is wrong --

440
0:20:41.589,000 --> 0:20:42,000
and they'd put it in their drawer.

441
0:20:43.24,000 --> 0:20:44,000
And the company got sick of that,

442
0:20:44.844,000 --> 0:20:46,000
so they said, "This version, we're not going to do anything,

443
0:20:47.704,000 --> 0:20:48,000
but make sure it's darned accurate."

444
0:20:49.461,000 --> 0:20:5,000
And so that's what they did.

445
0:20:50.834,000 --> 0:20:52,000
This cult of doing things right is starting to spread.

446
0:20:53.446,000 --> 0:20:56,000
So, my final advice for those of you who are consumers of this technology:

447
0:20:56.966,000 --> 0:21:,000
remember, if it doesn't work, it's not necessarily you, ok?

448
0:21:01,000 --> 0:21:03,000
It could be the design of the thing you're using.

449
0:21:03.358,000 --> 0:21:05,000
Be aware in life of good design and bad design.

450
0:21:06.17,000 --> 0:21:08,000
And if you're among the people who create this stuff:

451
0:21:09.061,000 --> 0:21:1,000
Easy is hard.

452
0:21:10.404,000 --> 0:21:12,000
Pre-sweat the details for your audience.

453
0:21:12.762,000 --> 0:21:13,000
Count the taps.

454
0:21:14,000 --> 0:21:16,000
Remember, the hard part is not deciding what features to add,

455
0:21:16.967,000 --> 0:21:17,000
it's deciding what to leave out.

456
0:21:18.76,000 --> 0:21:21,000
And best of all, your motivation is: simplicity sells.

457
0:21:22.611,000 --> 0:21:23,000
CA: Bravo. DP: Thank you very much.

458
0:21:24.302,000 --> 0:21:25,000
CA: Hear, hear!

459
